P018|2512.19575|Train and sample discrete Ising and continuous phi4 models without reference data.|PDF p. 1 abstract.|Combine reinforcement learning with variational autoregressive networks and add single-site or block Metropolis-Hastings corrections to VAN proposals.|PDF p. 1 abstract and contents Sec. 2.4.|For the explored ranges, MH corrections reduce residual bias, results agree with standard Monte Carlo within errors, and no clear critical slowing down is observed.|PDF p. 1 abstract.|The evidence is for the reported Ising and phi4 settings and uses ESS alongside corrections; it does not itself establish a universal wall-time win.|PDF p. 1 abstract.|direct_root_citation|SPS reference [11], printed p. 30 (PDF page 31).|Data-free autoregressive proposals plus MH correction are a direct SPS-family comparison with an explicit residual-bias boundary.|VAN eliminates critical slowing down in all regimes.|Compare corrected observable errors and training plus sampling cost.
P019|2604.10209|Address critical slowing down and scaling limits of single-scale learned lattice samplers near criticality.|PDF p. 1 abstract and Sec. I.|Use a coarse-to-fine multiscale generative sampler with conditional Gaussian mixtures, masked continuous normalizing flows, and exact restriction maps for MLMC.|PDF p. 1 abstract.|For reported critical 2D phi4 studies, the method has much shorter integrated autocorrelation than HMC, high importance-sampling efficiency, and observables agreeing with long HMC simulations.|PDF p. 1 abstract.|The reported numerical claim is a 2D critical-phi4 result and must not be recast as a general cost-normalized theorem.|PDF p. 1 abstract.|method_adjacent|Current PDF p. 1; root predates no citation assertion.|Multiscale architecture and MLMC are a current alternative route to critical lattice sampling that needs observable-level cost comparison with SPS.|This proves every learned sampler scales favorably at criticality.|Compare total training, generation, and estimator cost at fixed volume.
P020|2605.11199|Expose what trained lattice samplers represent internally rather than judging them only by output ensembles.|PDF p. 1 summary and Sec. I.|Project a trained velocity, score, or learned-action residual onto symmetry-fixed operator dictionaries and retain sectors only when held-out and control tests support them.|PDF pp. 1-2, Secs. I-II.|The paper reports separable zero-mode and finite-momentum residual sectors in 2D phi4 and analogous diagnostics for diffusion, normalizing-flow, and gauge-equivariant teachers.|PDF p. 1 summary.|Operator spectroscopy is a diagnostic of learned functions; it is not by itself a sampling-efficiency benchmark.|PDF p. 1 summary and Sec. I.|direct_root_citation|SPS reference [32], printed p. 31 (PDF page 32).|Operator spectroscopy gives a mechanistic audit that can complement ensemble-level SPS diagnostics.|A low projection residual proves a sampler is exact or fast.|Apply the diagnostic to a trained SPS model and compare it with observable tests.
